----------


Your [IDE][1] might suggest replacing that inner loop with a call to `addAll`.

```java
for ( String line : input.lines ( ).toList ( ) )
{
    for ( String pair : line.split ( &quot;,&quot; ) )
    {
        list.addAll ( Arrays.asList ( pair.split ( &quot;=&quot; ) ) );
    }
}
```


----------


For even more compact code, we can use streams and `flatMap` to produce a one-liner.

```java
String[] array =
        input
                .lines ( )
                .flatMap ( line -&gt; Arrays.stream ( line.split ( &quot;,&quot; ) ) )
                .flatMap ( pair -&gt; Arrays.stream ( pair.split ( &quot;=&quot; ) ) )
                .toArray ( String[] :: new );
```


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_development_environment

You should delimit your data one step at a time, and parse one line at a time rather than doing it all at once.

So in your case, each line (content.nextLine) should be split by a comma:

    String attributes = line.split(&#39;,&#39;);

Then, take your *attributes* and split them individually to get your key and value:

    for(String attribute : attributes) {
        String pairs = attribute.split(&#39;=&#39;);
        String key = attribute[0]; // Event, or time
        String value = attribute[1]; // LightsOn, or 2000

        // Do stuff with key and value, like add in your array
    }

As a side note:

Unless you are required to add it to a primitive array, I would recommend making an object to represent the data you are parsing. That way you can just add a new object of that data (i.e. Event(String name, long time)) into an ArrayList of Events.

